posts.com:
September 11, 2001 has had an incredible impact on my life. I remember thinking that day that it was going to be something I would never forget. Hardly a day goes by that I don’t think about it. It was the day Nickelback’s album Silver Side Up was released.
I went to Walmart to buy it. The cashier was crying. She must have already listened to it and was affected by some of the more emotional songs.
On the way home I popped it into my CD player. I was blown away by it from the very first moment. I tired to stop at a gas station, but for some reason they were all crowded. I guess it was all the people going out to buy the new album. When I got home my parents asked me if I had heard the news. I told them I already knew about the new Nickelback album. I went to my room to listen to it. Every song was amazing and the track layout was perfect. The cover art was awesome. Chad Kroeger and the other guys looked like the epitome of rockstars. It was an incredible work of genius and I could understand why the cashier was so emotional. I had loved Curb and The State, but this was something completely new and different from my favorite band. My parents were watching the news really loud so I had to turn it up to drown that out. I played it on repeat over and over until I fell asleep. It was one of the most memorable days of my life. I can’t even begin to imagine what my life would be like without Silver Side Up.

>>114402252
the thing about making sample based beats especially if you're trying to do the 90s boom bap feel is that in terms of melody there is only ever slight variation on a main motif and maybe another element or two for a hook but those would be high passed and eating up very little of the main part of the mix. the way you keep a beat interesting is by throwing in a bunch of unique sounds and textures that play only once or maybe twice throughout the beat once you have it laid out. it takes less effort than you think and once you get the hang of it you can start using it to really build and accentuate energy as opposed to just making things less repetitive.
doing the whole a/b/c verse/chorus/bridge with unique progression for each is not the type of sectioning you tend to see in hip hop.

>>114406121
I work on more than one project, maybe 10 or so.
I just go with the flow, look into this project or the other project. Do what i enjoy right now, either build a pattern, play around with synth, make a melody or play with some effects. Or i start a new project.

There are at least 2 dozen new tracks, but keep myself only active on 8 to 10 tracks. I can finish a track on one day, 8 hours max. Sometimes i produce into the night and when i wake up the next morning i finish the track. But i also have tracks i don't want to finish, i keep them in the production stage on purpose just for fun.

Thats the thing right here, do not start your daw with the expectation to finish a song. Start it with a different intend, see what direction this goes, save it and keep it for later use, or just build some presets for a random vst, make your own samples, etc etc etc....

>>114421714
the panning is as if you have just discovered that stereo audio exists; not only do you not need to hardpan stuff, but anything below, say, 150 hz (but probably more, say 300 hz or something) should be completely mono. stereo imaging on low frequency stuff should be avoided. the sidechaining is fine, it's stylistic so i won't make any value judgment, but you could probably afford a faster release on it. also re: the fact that elements in the R channel are sidechained to elements (the kick) that aren't in the R channel literally at all is extremely jarring. the percussion needs to brought waaay up in the mix, it is almost completely lost atm. bring it up in the mix and add some parallel compression to it. i think you could also crank some saturation on the kick/bass elements... really everything, to be honest. neat track, but needs a lot of love in the mixing department.

>>114407431
If you dedicate 2 hours a day consistently you've got more of a drive than 95% of musicians out there, including professionals. Just be aware that until you build up lactic acid tolerance and calluses you will not have the stamina to do so. Additionally if you do find your drive waning, it's better to do say, 20 minutes every day rather than several hours once a week.

I personally started on guitar before playing bass, and I should warn all beginners who do the same that the initial hurdle (memorising the basic chord shapes and being able to smoothly transition between them) is probably the hardest one, which can be quite discouraging. However, once you've got that to be second nature, everything past that seems comparatively easy (although I'm not hugely technically proficient myself by any means, so I can't necessarily speak for really advanced stuff like 6 string sweep picking).

You will need DAW (digital audio workstation) to have somewhere to record the audio from the interface to, I personally recommend Ableton but it's really a matter of personal choice. Most DAW's inbuilt virtual amps suck though, so you might wanna splash out a couple hundred bucks on Bias FX2

>owning multiple different instruments
What matters most when getting sound out of your guitar is your skill as a player, and the amp/pedals you choose. I will get called a poorfag for this, but the guitar itself plays a smaller part than people realize. The few exceptions to this (for a beginner) are if you plan on playing genres with "clean" setups (minimal effects) for genres like jazz or bossa, or want to emulate something specific as accurately as you can.

Pick your first guitar based on your gut, preferably after getting a feel for it at a music shop. Save the multiple instruments stuff for once you've put a year or two into it. No point in going all in if you don't know you're in it for the longhaul.

>>114421251
There is no spoonfeeding you have to use your ear its unique to the equipment you own, I can give you tips on how to achieve it but its up to you to get there.

1. EQ, Start with one at a time at max setting and roll it back till its not shrill, harsh, fwubby, wolfy etc. Your EQ will change slightly depending on the volume you are playing generally bigger amps need less bass EQ.

2. Guitar, don't play with max volume, keep your guitar at about an 8 same with the tone knobs, that way if you need a little extra high or volume to cut through you can just dial it in on your guitar.

3. Pedals, be sure you keep your pedal chain in the correct order, use google for correct chain order, again to dial them in start at max and roll back till the shrill harshness goes away.

A shitty amp will always sound shitty assuming the cabinet and speaker is shitty, the biggest tone shaper to the electric guitar is the speaker.

You can't think of the chords of the standards as individual chords, anon.

If you see, I don't know, Fm7 - Bb7b9 - Ebmaj9 for instance, you can't think of those as three different chords, but you need to realise that it's a ii - V - I in the key of Eb major.

>>114425419
Oh obviously, the best thing you can do at first is to just learn at least two options for playing major 2-5-1's : one version where your 2's root note will be played on the low E string (and the next chords will be accordingly close on the neck from this starting chord), and another where the root of your 2 chord will be on the A string.

For example, for Am7 - D7 - Gmaj7, have one version starting from the Am7 voiced like 5-x-5-5-5-5, and another where it's voiced as x-12-10-12-12-x (okay it's an Am9 but it'll usually work in major keys)

What this does is allow you to have at least two options for every possible (major) 2-5-1 you might encounter in a jazz standard, so when you're first learning them, you can look at, say, "Dm7 - G7 - C" and just think "oh yeah I can take that shape I know and move it here, or take that other shape I also know and move it there", depending on which one will need the smallest jump from wherever you were on your guitar neck.

You don't need to be super fancy at first, the endless options for extensions, substitutions, etc, can come later. Just pick some shapes that work and apply them on simple standards so you can already get a feel for learning a song without thinking of the chords as individual things, but as building blocks that can move around your guitar's neck.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Loveless is objectively the best album of all time. Apart from being the pinnacle of a genre that was just born, becoming both a defining as well as end-game work, it encapsulated a unique approach not just to the guitar sound, but song writing as a whole. Since it came out, you could say that several *single songs* from it went on to define the sound of different styles or even bands. It's like if jimi hendrix released a record where every song had the impact of watchtower.
Of course we have to address the guitar textures. Noise is surprisingly difficult to play with, because if you just turn up the distortion it's easy to end up with a sound that is the same regardless of what notes you play... Like a jet engine. That's why historically power chords have been so prominent in rock: they sounded decent when distorted. Mbv on the other hand like no other band to date has been able to create a truly _meaningful noise_, one deeply imbued with harmony and feelings. I'd argue never before has there been such a big leap forward in sound design, unless you count microphone technology advancements in the 60s.
I do understand all of the hate though. This is a challenging record, in the sense that even 30 years later it sounds revolutionary; and I suspect the people who don't understand the greatness they are witnessing nevertheless feel it and so fear it. You feel the need to dismiss it because it puts your world upside down and you can't easily box it in one of your typical concepts like "dad rock" or "(c)rap" or "indie shit". Do not cry though, for there is a remedy: listen to it. Many times. You'll understand.

Damn, what did you use to make this one?
That sci fi like synth in seccion 1 sounds very organic. It doesnt have much melodic content yet it manages to stay interesting and keep the attention thorougt the whole duration
Seccion 2 is very relaxing and at the same time it keeps a background tension with the background noise, which blends seemingly with seccion 3, which has nice leads
Seccion 4 has that cool sci fi synth again, and the percussion here is more driven. I also like the fast repeating sounds echoed in various instruments by the middle
Some cool pads in seccion 5 but to me it was the less interesting one for some reason

>>114404898
Thanks for the kind words! Haven't listened to any unicorns yet but I'll put that on the to-do.
Some advice for lyrical stuff, take-it-or-leave-it - when I started writing lyrics maybe five years ago I remembered everything came out really cringe, and my assumption was that everything sounds kinda cringe to the guy who writes it and you just have to overcome the hurdle of being unsure about yourself in order to put good things out into the world. With hindsight, those lyrics really *were* bad and the part of me that was saying they sucked was *right,* though it was probably good for me to learn to do the sort of ego-relinquishing that comes with showing someone something you made that still makes you squirm a little.

The trick I picked up that made everything way better was to just keep a file of notes on my phone with little fragments of ideas I would come up with throughout the day. At one point I did a project where I wrote a song every day before breakfast, and I relied pretty heavily on the file of notes (which was pretty big at that point), and it really wasn't hard to find matches for instrumentals and lyrical ideas that either fit nicely together or made for bizarre and cool juxtapositions. Don Hertzfeldt, one of my favorite directors, apparently has a process kind of like this. I think this process made everything way easier since I wasn't really sitting down and telling myself "okay time to generate good ideas" anymore, which, in my case, led to a lot of crap.

I used to be cynical about this kind of approach (Rivers Cuomo takes this way too fuckin far, see his episode of song exploder), and it is more of a brian eno-y process than a flash-of-great-inspiration thing, but it helped me to realize that I have some kind of potential to write good things, and that's kind of half the battle right there.

Oops sorry for writing ten paragraphs

Haha rivers cuomo is the weezer guy. Here's the Don Hertzfeldt quote I was thinking of:

>It's like you're floating in an ocean, and you want to build a raft. So you just float there and you wait and wait. And eventually this little piece of something comes drifting by, maybe a memory, and you hang on to it, and then another little piece comes around, it is unrelated, maybe it's a funny sentence you overheard somewhere. And you keep collecting all these little things that just sort of drift by... a dream, a beautiful sentence in your head that just appeared while doing the dishes, an anecdote you stole from your old diary... and eventually you find connections between all the things and with all these parts you've gathered up you now have enough stuff to build a raft. And then once you have the raft you can remove all the bits that don't quite fit anymore, the spare parts that you didn't need after all, you toss them back or maybe save them for another raft later. When I write, there isn't a lot of active effort or swimming around, or calculation... for me that can be very poisonous to creativity. The big ideas won't happen right when you mentally stress on them... it's more a matter of being patient and being open to all the things that just drift in.

Oldfag here.

Motley came out of the 70's glam scene, and what WASP were doing. Alice Cooper was still in his bottle at that point. When the Crue broke out, they were playing with stale, dated late 70's AOR bands. Nobody looked like the Crue, or sounded like them...except WASP, and more obscure Strip bands like London - which had Nikki in it. They were in at the start of a glam revival in LA and SF. The mainstream was bands like Rush, April Wine - AOR. And here you have Motley with leather, studs, candelabras, stage production, etc. That's why they went up to the Bay Area and blew the Bay Area home town band TY&T off the stage at a Halloween show that's infamous now. They were getting ALL the shock value. And, their album was really good - Live Wire sounded more like what was getting imported with the NWOBHM bands, not the bloated bands on the charts in '81/82.
They had the look. They had the production. They had the songs. They had the right producers - they had Roy Fucking Thomas Baker remix the debut. They had a label pushing them, and they had the videos for MTV with all the shock value. Girls wanted to fuck Vince, Nikki and Tommy (and did), and the guys wanted to play like Mick.
Luck? LOL. No. They had a vision, they had backing, and they had the talent. And it worked. That's why they went from nothing to ruling the Strip in less than a year, and became millionaires the next year, and put out two albums that both went multiplatinum. They did everything right, and luck had fuck all to do with it. They were such a god damn juggernaught Vince got away with killing someone.
But you keep thinking luck had anything to do with it. I'm not a huge fan of the band, but to call their success in the early years luck just shows how young and naive you are.

posts.com:
Whenever people discuss Nine Inch Nails two albums always get overlooked.

The boomers won't shut up about how they grew up with Pretty Hate Machine, Downward Spiral is the mainstream pick for "best NIN album". The Fragile is the safe contrarian pick for best NIN album and largely considered second greatest by critics. With Teeth is often talked about because of the divide between fans - is it the most boring or simply the catchiest and most fun? Hesitation Marks has a similar appeal for discussion in that half the fans hate that album with an unbridled passion while the staunch contrarians claim "it's actually Trent's best work, you just don't understand."

Year Zero and The Slip are constantly overlooked despite both being very good entries in NIN discography. Both albums are largely enjoyed by the fanbase and critics but because they're more "mid" in a literal sense. They never get the discussion they deserve. They aren't beloved like PHM-The Fragile and they're not as controversial as HM and With Teeth.

Let's talk about these two albums. Lights in the Sky is the best ballad Trent ever made.
